Show when someone is typing
Load only part of a conversation and dynamically load more
Forbid self-messages
Translations
Saved states
Don't crash when connection to server cannot be established or is lost
The server should generally not be trusted. However, there is one scenario where trusting the server would be a good thing: Let's say you remove a friend. Now you have verified the friend request and it could be sent to you again to show you are still friends, even though you removed them. If you trust the server, you know that this won't happen. There is one problem with this that the ex-friend can store the original friend request, somehow get the ip and port of your websocket and pretend to be the server. At this point, they can show you the original friend request and your client will think you're friends. This is why the server should authenticate such a thing with a signature and a timestamp too, so that if the ex-friend tries to do this, he cannot sign the message and your client will reject it. This is not a security issue. If you have to trust the server for security, your application is not secure. It is, however, a convenience issue.
